data.title: Emma Thompson says she was 'utterly blind' to her ex husband having an affair with Harry Potter star
data.meta_description: Emma Thompson admitted she was 'utterly blind' to her ex husband Kenneth Branagh having an affair with Helena Bonham Carter.
data.text:
Emma Thompson has admitted she was 'utterly blind' to her ex-husband Kenneth Branagh's affair with Helena Bonham Carter and said she felt 'unlovable' after finding out.

The actress, 63, married Kenneth, 61, back in 1989 just two years after they met, but his affair with Helena ended their six-year marriage in 1995.

Helena, now 56, is believed to have started an affair with Kenneth in 1994 while she played his love interest in his version of Mary Shelley's Frankenstein. They went on to have a five-year relationship.

Speaking to the New Yorker, Emma admitted she felt 'humiliated' by the affair and felt that she was 'unlovable' after being left devastated by Kenneth's unfaithfulness.

She told the publication: 'I was utterly, utterly blind to the fact that he had relationships with other women on set.

'What I learned was how easy it is to be blinded by your own desire to deceive yourself.'

'I was half alive. Any sense of being a lovable or worthy person had gone completely,' she added.

Two years before Helena met Kenneth and their affair began, she had worked with Emma on 1992 romance drama film Howard's End.

Since the affair, the pair have also worked together on the Harry Potter series, with Emma playing Professor Trelawney and Helena starring as Bellatrix Lestrange.

Emma has previously admitted that she had long 'forgiven' Helena and channelled her feelings of betrayal into playing a wronged wife in hit film Love Actually.

Revealing how she recovered from the devastation, Emma said it was her now husband of 27 years Greg Wise who 'picked up the pieces and put them back together'.

Reflecting on her marriage to Greg, she added: 'I've learned more from my second marriage just by being married. As my mother says, "The first twenty years are the hardest."

Emma met Greg while filming Sense and Sensibility in 1995, which won an Oscar for Best Adapted Screenplay.

However, the news of her and Kenneth's break-up had not yet been made public at the time she was filming the period drama.

It is not the first time that Emma has spoken out about Kenneth and Helena's affair, previously admitting she had 'forgiven' Helena for the betrayal.

In 2013, she said the break-up was 'all blood under the bridge', adding: 'You can't hold on to anything like that.

'It's pointless. I haven't got the energy for it. Helena and I made our peace years and years ago.'

She has also spoken candidly about the depression that she suffered following the end of her marriage in 1995.

Emma said she channelled her feelings of betrayal into her portrayal of a wronged wife in Richard Curtis's romantic comedy Love Actually.

'I've had so much bloody practice at crying in a bedroom, then having to go out and be cheerful, gathering up the pieces of my heart and putting them in a drawer,' she said.

She also admitted that there are similarities between her and Helena which may have appealed to Kenneth, saying: 'Being slightly mad and a bit fashion-challenged.

'Perhaps that's why Ken loved us both. She's a wonderful woman, Helena.'

In 2002, Helena said her relationships had been misunderstood, alluding to allegations of her affair with Kenneth.

'Yes. I'm a habitual, serial home breaker, apparently,' she said. 'It gets frustrating because I know the story and the truth of it.'

Helena has two children, Billy and Nell, with her ex-partner film director Tim Burton. The pair split after 13 years together.

Emma and Greg married in 2003 and they share two children, a daughter Gaia, 22, and a son Tindyebwa, a former child soldier from Rwanda whom they informally adopted when he was 16.

The same year that the happy couple tied the knot, Kenneth also married art director Lindsay Brunnock, and they are still together today.
